                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="partly Ethiopian">
                              <p>The boards and the slip-case may be contemporary to the production of the unit of circulation, while the sewing and the leather cover are a later addition.</p>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="bindingMaterial">
                                  The book is bound in <material key="wood">wooden</material> boards partially covered with reddish-brown <material key="leather">leather</material>.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="Boards">
                                  The boards are few millimeters larger than the bookblock and have external shallow bevels.<!-- The upper board seems to have inner bevels as well--> The grain runs vertically.
                                  On the inner surface of both boards, along the inner magin, leather fibers and traces of glue are present.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Cover" color="reddish-brown">
                                  The boards and the spine are partially covered with plain reddish-brown leather.
                                  The upper board is almost entirely covered, while only half of the lower board is. The turn-ins are not well adhered and are partially detached from the boards.
                                  The irregular cut, its smaller size compared to the bookblock and the absence of decoration suggest that the cover was a hasty, posthumous addition to the binding.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b4" type="Endbands" color="brown">
                                  Brown <term key="slitBraid">slit-braid</term> brown endbands are present.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b5" type="Sewing">
                                  The bookblock was originally sewn on four sewing stations (two pairs) with S-plied threads resulting in a periodic fold pattern.
                                  However, the original sewing is not preserved and only the marks left by the threads in the quires, the holes in the boards and in the quires remain.
                                  As of today, each quire is stitched through the inner margin in correspondence of the uppermost and lowermost sewing stations.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="SewingStations">2</decoNote>

                                <decoNote xml:id="b7" type="Spine">
                                  Vertical short stitches pierce the leather on the spine in two points at the head and tail of each quire, thus fixing the endbands to the cover.
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b8" type="SlipCase">
                                  The manuscript is provided with a leather two-piece slip case with a strap. The inner case is single-walled and equipped with long flaps
                                  extending from the side panels and a main tapered flap extending from the back to the front panel, to cover the opening of the book compartment.
                                  The outer case slides along the hanging strap to fit over the inner case. The strap used to pass through two pouches
                                  sewn to the lateral panels of the inner case and the top panel of the outer case but it is now fixed just to the inner case.
                                  A sticker with the inventory number "23451" is glued onto one side of the case.</decoNote>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b9" type="Other">
                                  Threads of various origin are inserted in the outer margins in correspondence of the incipit of the weekday readings.
                                  More specifically, a bright red <term key="leafStringMark">leaf string mark</term> is inserted in the outer margin of <locus target="#16"/> and
                                  a piece of textile of the same type is inserted on <locus target="#17ra"/>. Other coloured or uncoloured <term key="leafStringMark">leaf string markers</term>
                                  are inserted in the outer margins of <locus target="#20 #40 #61"/>.
                                  A fragment of the same bright red textile used as a leaf tab marker is placed between <locus target="#16"/> and <locus target="#17"/>.
                                  A straw from a plant is placed between <locus target="#68"/> and <locus target="#69"/>.
                                </decoNote>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>

